The Group-Based Population Algorithm (GPBA)38 is used to update the existing population after M new solutions have been made utilizing the clustering-driven alteration strategy. The GPBA is a complex method that aims to make the optimization process work better overall. This method breaks the population up into smaller groups that are easier to handle. The solutions work together and change within each group, which makes optimization more targeted and effective within each subset of the population. One of the best things about the GPBA is that it keeps the population diverse. The approach lowers the chance of premature convergence by working in smaller groups. This is a common problem with classic optimization methods, where the whole population could fast converge to a local optimum. This method of working in groups makes sure that different parts of the solution space are looked at, which makes it more likely that a global optimum will be found. The GPBA is also quite efficient when it comes to using computational resources, which is another big plus. By dividing the population into groups, the method can speed up the optimization process by making it possible for multiple groups to work on it at the same time. This is especially helpful when dealing with complicated problems and big groups of people, where time and computing power are quite important. In addition, the GPBA makes it easier for people to adapt and learn. Each group can change its search technique based on what they find out in their area, which makes the optimization process more flexible and responsive. This change to fit the local area can help find better answers that algorithms that just look at global population dynamics might miss.
