In our proposed DE framework, the objective function plays a vital role in assessing the effectiveness of each potential solution. All objective functions in DE-based training have relied on the discrepancy between actual and predicted outputs39. In this paper, we present a novel approach by integrating a regularization component into the objective function, structured as follows:3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{1}{N}\mathop \sum \limits_{i = 1}^{N} \left( {y_{i} - \tilde{y}_{i} } \right)^{2} + \frac{\lambda }{2m}\sum \left| W \right|$$\end{document}where N symbolizes the aggregate of training instances, with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$y_{i} { }$$\end{document} representing the i-th actual target and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\tilde{y}_{i}$$\end{document} the i-th output forecasted by the model. The term m signifies the total count of weight matrices that necessitate optimization. The parameter λ is denoted as the regularization parameter and can be perceived as a hyperparameter. The regularization term possesses the capability to penalize exceedingly large magnitudes of weights and biases. Should λ be chosen excessively large, numerous weights are likely to approach zero, simplifying the model and potentially rendering it susceptible to underfitting. Conversely, if λ is chosen to be overly diminutive, the impact of the regularization term may become nullified in practical scenarios. When λ is judiciously selected, it can selectively dampen certain weights, mitigating the risk of overfitting.

